  "body": "## Note: I'm running this on Windows Subsystem for Linux 2 (WSL2)\r\n\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\n```\r\nGeth\r\nVersion: 1.9.15-stable\r\nGit Commit: 0f77f34bb67b640bd8af22b215f3d279a1e21170\r\nArchitecture: amd64\r\nProtocol Versions: [65 64 63]\r\nGo Version: go1.14.2\r\nOperating System: linux\r\n```\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nrunning `geth --ipcdisable --shh dumpconfig` should generate a config file that both disables ipc and enables shh\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nWhen doing `geth dumpconfig` with some flags, such as `--shh` or `--ipcdisable`, the output toml file doesn't actually enable shh or disable ipc...\r\n\r\nI'm not sure if there are other options that are not being translated to the config file, but I did run into both `shh` and `ipcdisable` today.\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n```\r\ngeth --ipcdisable dumpconfig > disabled.cfg\r\ngeth dumpconfig > enabled.cfg\r\n\r\ndiff enabled.cfg disabled.cfg\r\n60d59\r\n< IPCPath = \"geth.ipc\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nHowever...when I try to actually run the disabled.cfg config file:\r\n`Fatal: Error starting protocol stack: listen unix /mnt/e/geth/data/geth.ipc: bind: operation not supported`\r\n\r\nI assume this is because it's assuming the default here, there isn't actually a property in the config that is disabling it.\r\n\r\nThe workaround is obviously to specify the options on the cli command, but it should be set in the toml file...",
